# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# .env.bootstrap.example — OPTIONAL automation/CI bootstrap input
#
# For the interactive RAM-only path, you do NOT need this file:
#   docker compose --profile bootstrap run --rm -it bootstrap
#
# Use this file when:
# - you want repeatable app-owned adapter setup
# - you are provisioning custom app adapters such as LiteLLM or OpenWebUI
# - you are running headless / CI automation
#
# Automation path:
#   cp .env.bootstrap.example .env.bootstrap
#   # edit .env.bootstrap with real values
#   ./bootstrap.sh
#
# NEVER commit .env.bootstrap — .gitignore blocks it, but verify.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── Provider API keys to encrypt ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# Values in this file are plaintext until bootstrap finishes. `./bootstrap.sh`
# shreds `.env.bootstrap` after a successful run.
#
# Automation contract for each direct secret slot:
#   <SECRET_ENV>=<secret>
#   <KEY_ID_ENV>=<key_id>
#   <SECRET_ENV>_ADAPTERS=<comma-separated declared app adapter IDs>
#
# Leave <SECRET_ENV>_ADAPTERS blank only for explicit compatibility/simple mode.
# That binds the key to the shared `subumbra-proxy` adapter on purpose.
#
# Example app-bound keys:
OPENAI_KEY=<your_openai_key>
OPENAI_KEY_ID=openai_litellm_1
OPENAI_KEY_ADAPTERS=litellm
UNIQUE_KEY_openai_litellm_1=false

OPENAI_KEY_2=<your_second_openai_key>
OPENAI_KEY_ID_2=openai_openwebui_1
OPENAI_KEY_2_ADAPTERS=openwebui
UNIQUE_KEY_openai_openwebui_1=true

# Example explicit compatibility/simple key:
# ANTHROPIC_KEY=<your_anthropic_key>
# ANTHROPIC_KEY_ID=anthropic_shared_1
# ANTHROPIC_KEY_ADAPTERS=
# UNIQUE_KEY_anthropic_shared_1=false

# ── Cloudflare credentials ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Create an API token at: https://dash.cloudflare.com/profile/api-tokens
# Required permissions: Workers Scripts:Edit, Workers KV Storage:Edit
CF_API_TOKEN=REPLACE_ME
CF_ACCOUNT_ID=REPLACE_ME
CF_WORKER_NAME=subumbra-proxy
TOKEN_TTL_DAYS=90

# ── Adapter identities ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Declare the custom app adapters that should receive generated
# SUBUMBRA_TOKEN_<APP> values.
#
# Example:
# ADAPTER_IDS=litellm,openwebui
#
# Built-ins remain automatic:
# - subumbra-proxy       (shared compatibility/simple mode only)
# - subumbra-ui          (metadata only; keep UI_ALLOWED_KEYS empty)
# - subumbra-probe       (optional diagnostics only)
ADAPTER_IDS=litellm,openwebui
PROBE_ALLOWED_KEYS=
UI_ALLOWED_KEYS=

# Optional external policy file for policy-backed bootstrap ingestion.
# If set, this must point to a host JSON file; ./bootstrap.sh mounts it
# read-only into the bootstrap container automatically.
# SUBUMBRA_POLICY_PATH=/opt/subumbra/policies.json

# ── Optional app-owned .env imports (consumed by ./bootstrap.sh) ──────────────
# IMPORT_PATH_<n> must point to a host file. ./bootstrap.sh mounts it readonly
# into the bootstrap container and passes the in-container path automatically.
# IMPORT_APP_LABEL_<n> is required for each import and becomes both:
# - the generated key_id label: <provider>_<app_label>_<ordinal>
# - the app adapter bound to each imported key
#
# Example:
# IMPORT_PATH_1=/opt/litellm/.env
# IMPORT_APP_LABEL_1=litellm
# IMPORT_PATH_2=/opt/openwebui/.env
# IMPORT_APP_LABEL_2=openwebui

# ── Headless server auth (optional) ──────────────────────────────────────────
# On servers without a browser (CI/CD, Citadel, Docker), wrangler cannot open
# an OAuth flow. Set this to your CF API token to bypass OAuth entirely.
# The bootstrap container sets CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN from CF_API_TOKEN above
# automatically — this entry is only needed when running wrangler outside Docker.
# CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN=REPLACE_ME

# `SUBUMBRA_TOKEN_PROXY` is not an app credential in the normal app-bound path.
# Use per-app tokens such as SUBUMBRA_TOKEN_LITELLM or SUBUMBRA_TOKEN_OPENWEBUI.
# Only use proxy token language for explicit compatibility/simple mode.
